content.description:
Start beneath the 8 inch shallow crack high on the bulge.  Work up the 5.7ish face to the difficult moves that overcome the bulge at the top.               

Wave wall beta photo.
content.protection: Top system from trees and gear.
content.location: The Mustard color route in the beta photos.

content.description:
Start about 5 feet left of the large inside corner that separates the J and Wave Walls. Climb the face following the thin crack up to the bulge. Work thru the bulge to the top.               

Wave wall beta photo.
content.protection: Top system from gear and small trees.
content.location: The Teal color route in the beta photos.

content.description:
Start at the hole beneath a crack with white quartz crystals. Work up the crack until the bare finish is reached. Climb the thin holds and smears as the angle of the face breaks.               

Wave wall beta photo.
content.protection: Top system from gear and small trees.
content.location: The Red color route in the beta photo.

content.description: Jump start to a good hold. Heel hook and use good hand holds to the left to get off the ground. Advance your way up the wall using good holds in cracks. Finish once you've reached the top. Video Beta: youtube.com/watch?v=HhrwdM9…
content.protection: Boulders can be used to set up a natural top rope anchor
content.location: Above the cave section to the right of Red Route.

content.description:
Start on the right side of the J Wall. Climb the overhanging face to the top. Do not use the crack to the left. The climber side of the large crack to the right can be used. Do not stem on the right wall. Finish the climb cleanly without using your knee or stepping left onto the ledge.               

J wall beta photo.
content.protection: Long top system from gear and small trees.
content.location: The Red route on the J Wall beta photo.

content.description:
Start on the left side of the J Wall between the left edge and the splitter hand crack. Climb the face straight up to the top.               

J wall beta photo.
content.protection: Top system from tress and gear.  A longish static line is required to hang down low enough to avoid drag at the top.
content.location: The Yellow route on the beta photo.

content.description:
The short left curving hand crack on the J Wall. Climb the crack using classic hand jams.                

J wall beta photo.
content.protection: Top system from gear and vegetation.
content.location: The J Wall is the left wall on the southern most outcrop.

content.description: Start on the right side of the wall. Climb up the corner, around the tree until you can move left onto the top of the roof. Climb the rest of the way up using good holds on cracks. It Shares the same top section as Might as well jump.Video Beta: youtube.com/watch?v=uuO9Mio…
content.protection: Boulders can be used to set up a natural top rope anchor.
content.location: Above the cave section to the right of Red Route.

content.description:
At the junction of the J Wall to the left and the Wave Wall to the right is a large crack. Climb the crack and/or the right face up to the overhanging bulge.  Surmount the bulge and get on the ledge without getting sucked into the awkward chimney moves.  Skip the ledge and finish above on the face to the right to notch the grade up to 5.7.                

J wall beta photo.
content.protection: Long top systems from fixed gear and small trees.
content.location:
The Purple route on the beta photos.               

Wave wall beta photo.

content.description:
The Wave and J Walls face East and North. They are fairly short but can provide hours of fun for a small group. Access is about the same as Bushwhack Rock but with no bushwhack. I compiled route beta before learning that this area is in Indys Online Climbing Guide. I used the names from Indys guide where the routes match up. The beta photos are of what we climbed on our outing.              

J Wall on the left, Wave Wall on the right.
